<h1 id="exhibit-g">EXHIBIT G</h1>
<h1 id="void-consent-order-october-23-2025">VOID “CONSENT ORDER”
(OCTOBER 23, 2025)</h1>
<p><strong>IN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF CAMDEN COUNTY</strong> <strong>STATE
OF GEORGIA</strong></p>
<p>CHRISTYN E. JOHNSON, Plaintiff,</p>
<ol start="22" type="a">
<li></li>
</ol>
<p>WILLIAM R. JOHNSON, Defendant.</p>
<p>CIVIL ACTION FILE NO. 2025CV936</p>
<h2 id="document-1-void-consent-order-october-23-2025">DOCUMENT 1: VOID
CONSENT ORDER (OCTOBER 23, 2025)</h2>
<p><strong>IN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF CAMDEN COUNTY</strong> <strong>STATE
OF GEORGIA</strong></p>
<p>CHRISTYN E. JOHNSON, Plaintiff,</p>
<ol start="22" type="a">
<li></li>
</ol>
<p>WILLIAM JOHNSON, Defendant.</p>
<p>CIVIL ACTION FILE NO. 2025CV936</p>
<p><strong>CONSENT ORDER</strong></p>
<p>This matter came before the Court on October 23, 2025, upon the
Plaintiff’s Motion for Emergency Relief.</p>
<p>The Court having considered the Motion, the response, and the
applicable law, it is hereby:</p>
<p><strong>ORDERED AND ADJUDGED:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p><strong>TSP WITHDRAWAL:</strong> Defendant shall immediately
withdraw the entirety of his Thrift Savings Plan (TSP) account,
including all pre-marital and marital portions, to cure the marital
financial delinquencies.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>MORTGAGE PAYMENT:</strong> Defendant shall immediately
apply the withdrawn TSP funds to bring the marital residence mortgage
current and pay all associated fees and penalties.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>HOUSE SALE:</strong> The marital residence located at 401
Powderhorn Road, Saint Marys, Georgia 31558, shall be listed for sale no
later than Monday, October 27, 2025.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>REALTOR:</strong> If the parties cannot agree on a
realtor, they shall use Georgia-Kay Sutterfield with Coldwell Banker in
Kingsland, Georgia.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>PROCEEDS:</strong> All proceeds from the TSP withdrawal
and house sale shall be held in trust with Plaintiff’s attorney,
Jennifer L. McGhan, Esq., until further Order of the Court.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>ATTORNEY’S FEES:</strong> Defendant shall pay Plaintiff’s
attorney’s fees and costs in the amount of $10,000.00 from his share of
the proceeds.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>CONSENTED AS TO FORM AND CONTENT:</strong></p>
<hr />
<p>Joseph East, Esq. Attorney for Defendant October 23, 2025</p>
<hr />
<p>Jennifer L. McGhan, Esq. Attorney for Plaintiff October 23, 2025</p>
<p><strong>SIGNED THIS 23rd DAY OF OCTOBER, 2025</strong></p>
<hr />
<p>Honorable O. Brent Green Judge, Pro Hac Vice Camden County Superior
Court</p>
<h2 id="document-2-defendants-objection-to-void-order">DOCUMENT 2:
DEFENDANT’S OBJECTION TO VOID ORDER</h2>
<p><strong>TO:</strong> Camden County Superior Court
<strong>FROM:</strong> William R. Johnson, Pro Se <strong>DATE:</strong>
October 24, 2025 <strong>SUBJECT:</strong> Objection to Unauthorized
Hearing Notice and Motion for Sanctions</p>
<p><strong>LEGAL BASIS FOR OBJECTION:</strong></p>
<p><strong>1. FRAUD UPON THE COURT (Lewis v. Uselton
Standard)</strong></p>
<p>The “Consent Order” is void ab initio because: - Joseph East’s
authority to represent Defendant was terminated on October 19, 2025 -
East had actual knowledge of the termination (October 19, 2025 email) -
East signed the “Consented as to form and content” line without
authority - Plaintiff’s counsel had actual knowledge of the
termination</p>
<p><strong>2. LACK OF SUBJECT MATTER JURISDICTION (Adams v.
Payne)</strong></p>
<p>The hearing was presided over by Judge O. Brent Green, a Juvenile
Court Judge, without proper assignment: - No Order of Assignment filed
prior to October 16, 2025 hearing - Order of Assignment filed October
23, 2025 (nunc pro tunc) - Subject matter jurisdiction cannot be
conferred retroactively</p>
<p><strong>3. VIOLATION OF DUE PROCESS</strong></p>
<p>Defendant was not properly served with notice of the October 16, 2025
hearing: - No formal notice provided - Defendant was unrepresented at
the hearing - No opportunity to be heard on the merits</p>
<p><strong>4. FINANCIAL HARM AND DISSIPATION</strong></p>
<p>The order forces Defendant to: - Liquidate pre-marital TSP assets
(accumulated 2009-2015) - Incur unnecessary $7,079.19 in tax penalties -
Violate his ADA accommodation request for extended processing time</p>
<p><strong>RELIEF REQUESTED:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>VACATE</strong> the October 23, 2025 “Consent Order” as void
ab initio</li>
<li><strong>SANCTION</strong> Plaintiff’s counsel for filing fraudulent
documents</li>
<li><strong>AWARD</strong> Defendant damages for financial harm caused
by void order</li>
<li><strong>PROTECT</strong> Defendant’s pre-marital TSP assets from
improper division</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>VERIFICATION:</strong></p>
<p>I, William R. Johnson, being duly sworn, depose and say that I am the
Defendant in this action; that I have read the foregoing Objection; that
the facts stated therein are true and correct to the best of my
knowledge, information, and belief.</p>
<hr />
<p>William R. Johnson Defendant Pro Se October 24, 2025</p>
<h2 id="document-3-emergency-temporary-order-october-23-2025">DOCUMENT
3: EMERGENCY TEMPORARY ORDER (OCTOBER 23, 2025)</h2>
<p><strong>IN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF CAMDEN COUNTY</strong> <strong>STATE
OF GEORGIA</strong></p>
<p>CHRISTYN E. JOHNSON, Plaintiff,</p>
<ol start="22" type="a">
<li></li>
</ol>
<p>WILLIAM JOHNSON, Defendant.</p>
<p>CIVIL ACTION FILE NO. 2025CV936</p>
<p><strong>EMERGENCY TEMPORARY ORDER</strong></p>
<p>THIS CAUSE came on to be heard on October 23, 2025, upon the
Plaintiff Wife’s Ex Parte Motion for Emergency Relief.</p>
<p><strong>1. JURISDICTION:</strong> The Court has jurisdiction of the
parties to and the subject matter of this action.</p>
<p><strong>2. FINANCIAL DELINQUENCY:</strong> The Husband has refused to
take the steps necessary to cash out his Thrift Savings Plan (TSP) in
order to cure the many marital financial delinquencies, including the
mortgage payment(s), which is now three (3) months past due. This has
placed the parties’ only major asset, the marital home, in jeopardy of
foreclosure. Further, the mortgage is held in both parties’ names, thus
also jeopardizing the Wife’s credit.</p>
<p><strong>3. AGREEMENT:</strong> The parties had previously agreed to
allow the Husband one-hundred twenty (120) days to attempt to refinance
the marital home, with the understanding that the Husband would
immediately cash out his TSP to cure the three-month delinquency.</p>
<p><strong>4. HOUSE SALE:</strong> The marital home located at 401
Powderhorn Road, Saint Marys, Georgia 31558, shall be listed for sale no
later than Monday, October 27, 2025. If the parties cannot agree on a
realtor to list the property, the parties shall use Georgia-Kay
Sutterfield with Coldwell Banker in Kingsland, Georgia. The listing
price shall be determined by the realtor based on the market. The
parties are to promptly sign and deliver any and all documents required
to effectuate the sale of the home and shall accept any reasonable offer
within ninety-five percent (95%) of the home’s then-listed selling
price.</p>
<p><strong>5. PROCEEDS:</strong> Proceeds from the sale of the marital
home shall be held in trust with the Wife’s attorney, Jennifer L.
McGhan, Esq., McGhan Law, LLC, 575 E. King Avenue, Kingsland, Georgia
31548, until further Order of the Court.</p>
<p><strong>6. ATTORNEY’S FEES:</strong> The Wife is awarded attorney’s
fees and costs in the amount of $10,000.00. This sum shall be paid from
the Husband’s share of the proceeds from the sale of the marital
home.</p>
<p><strong>7. OTHER ISSUES:</strong> All remaining issues not addressed
herein are reserved.</p>
<p><strong>SO ORDERED</strong> this 23rd day of October, 2025.</p>
<hr />
<p>Honorable O. Brent Green Judge, Pro Hac Vice Camden County Superior
Court</p>
<h2 id="legal-significance">LEGAL SIGNIFICANCE</h2>
<p>This exhibit establishes:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Void Judgment:</strong> The “Consent Order” is void due to
terminated attorney authority</li>
<li><strong>Fraud Standard:</strong> Joseph East’s signature constitutes
fraud upon the court</li>
<li><strong>Jurisdictional Defect:</strong> Judge Green lacked subject
matter jurisdiction</li>
<li><strong>Due Process Violation:</strong> Defendant was not properly
noticed or represented</li>
<li><strong>Financial Harm:</strong> Order forces improper liquidation
and tax penalties</li>
<li><strong>Legal Precedent:</strong> Violates established Georgia case
law (Lewis v. Uselton, Adams v. Payne)</li>
</ol>
